<TEXT>
the airline industry and boeing co are 
welcoming government orders that will alter the way airlines keep 
aging passenger jets safe 
in a series of airworthiness directives announced thursday 
the federal aviation administration said it plans to order 161 
modifications on older boeing 727s 737s and 747s and will give 
airlines up to four years to comply 
we think this is an important step in the right direction and 
will further increase the already high levels of safety in the 
industry said stephen hayes vice president of the air transport 
association which represents airlines 
the directives are expected to become law by late summer after 
a period for comment and modification they would replace a method 
of dealing with aging airliners which requires periodic inspections 
and replacements only when parts show excessive wear 
the faa said its action marks a fundamental change in faas 
philosophy for maintaining the airworthiness of older aircraft 
the faa estimated the cost of modifying the 115 oldest jets at 
142 million other airliners would be affected as they age an 
industry group estimates the orders which have been anticipated 
for several months eventually will cost us and foreign airlines 
more than 800 million and affect 1300 planes 
a boeing statement said other countries aviation agencies are 
expected to adopt the orders 
high standards must be maintained to assure the safety of 
aging airplanes until economics dictate their retirement said 
ben cosgrove a boeing senior vice president 
only a handful of airliners have been retired in the last decade 
as traffic throughout the world continues to increase and orders 
for new jets are backlogged the average age of the worldwide fleet 
of passenger jets exceeds 13 years and aviation experts expect it 
to steadily increase 
the new directives will require replacement or strengthening of 
part of the fuselage wings doors tail assembly landing gear and 
engine struts of airliners as they age 
due to the magnitude of the modification program faa 
anticipates that the work will be staggered over a period of time 
and generally coordinated with other scheduled maintenance the 
agency said in explaining its decision to give airlines four years 
to comply 
the action was prompted partly by the april 1988 accident over 
hawaii in which a boeing 737 which had made almost 90000 flights 
lost an 18foot section of its fuselage a flight attendant was 
killed but the aircraft landed without any other fatalities 
the new requirements will force airlines to replace aging parts 
earlier in a planes life 60000 flights for 727s 75000 for 737s 
and 20000 for 747 jumbo jets the larger aircraft make fewer but 
longer flights airliners that reach 20 years old would also be 
affected even if they have logged fewer flights 
one requirement for 747s calls for a major modification of the 
fuselage shell structure from the nose to the forward main 
passenger entry door the faa estimates the work on that and 28 
other modifications will require 35000 man hours per airplane 
for 737s 58 changes are mandated requiring more than 14000 
man hours for 727s the 74 required modifications will take more 
than 17000 man hours to complete 
the faa said the orders would initially affect 67 boeing 727s 
28 boeing 737s and 20 boeing 747s owned by us airlines 
the faa action follows guidelines proposed feb 28 by a 
150member task force of aviation industry and government experts 
set up by the ata and the aerospace industries association 
at that time task force member clyde kizer told an interviewer 
that the aircraft that are out there right now are perfectly 
safe this supplies an extra protection margin 
other task forces are examining airliners manufactured by 
mcdonnell douglas and other aircraft builders and the faa said it 
plans to issue similar directives affecting other planes 
</TEXT>
