<TEXT>
raymond blackman one of the worlds leading 
experts on foreign navies and veteran editor of the renown military 
reference book janes fighting ships has died his family said 
today he was 78 
janes fighting ships is one of the volumes on military 
hardware and other subjects produced annually by the janes 
publishing house and studied by defense forces around the world 
blackman who edited fighting ships from 194973 died 
wednesday his family gave no cause of death he lived at 
portsmouth the home of a major royal navy base on the south coast 
of england 
born in portsmouth he joined the royal navy at the age of 16 
and served for 10 years having trained as a naval engineer 
he then took up journalism and became naval correspondent for 
the hampshire telegraph and post a local newspaper covering 
the portsmouth area 
he rejoined the royal navy at the outbreak of world war ii in 
1939 working in the mine design department at portsmouth 
developing mines and antisubmarine weapons 
after the war he returned to journalism and from 1946 to 1956 
was naval correspondent of the sunday times the weekly sister 
paper of the times of london 
he also wrote for technical publications on naval matters and 
broadcast on naval topics he first became associated with janes 
fighting ships in 1930 
the janes publishing empire was founded by british artist and 
journalist fred thomas jane in 1898 when he produced the first 
janes fighting ships the book was an instant success 
janes says information is gathered for the volumes by 
monitoring world publications on the subject questioning 
industrial sources and tapping the expert knowledge and sources of 
each editor 
as editor of janes fighting ships blackman was constantly 
in touch with more than 100 navies around the world and maintained 
a network of international contacts who helped confirm details when 
official information was lacking 
blackman was also the author of modern world book of ships 
in 1951 of successive editions of the worlds warships and of 
ships of the royal navy in 1973 
he was honored by queen elizabeth ii in 1970 by being made a 
member of the order of the british empire 
he is survived by his wife a son and a daughter 
</TEXT>
