the analyses that weve got for saskatchewan show no pcbs 
said don waite acting manager of environmental protection for the 
saskatchewan branch of the department 
bryan armstrong of environment canadas office in edmonton said 
tests on eight alberta samples and three manitoba samples also 
showed no presence of pcbs there was no immediate word on whether 
testing there will be cut back 
in saskatchewan four staffers were sent last week to north 
portal a border crossing 140 miles southeast of this provincial 
capital the action followed reports that millions of gallons of 
hazardous chemicals had been mixed with fuel in the united states 
and shipped illegally to canada since 1987 
the investigators stopped all fuel trucks entering the province 
and took roadside samples for testing 
since may 11 the department has tested 42 samples of gasoline 
diesel fuel and heating oil for the presence of pcbs 
polychlorinated biphenyls but so far no traces have been detected 
pcbs primarily used as an insulator in electrical equipment 
have been linked with cancer and were banned in canada in 1977 as 
well as in the united states by illegally mixing pcbladen wastes 
into fuels expensive disposal fees can be avoided 
the department said it will continue to perform random spot 
checks at north portal and will consider further tests at gas 
stations around the province 
armstrong said the problem of illegal shipments appears to be 
restricted to central canada 
but last week andrew porterfield a researcher for the 
washington dcbased center for investigative reporting told a 
vancouver radio station that fuel laced with hazardous wastes has 
been brought up through idaho and illegally dumped in british 
columbia and alberta 
