<TEXT>
voters edged away from northern 
irelands militant extremes and boosted moderates today on both 
sides of the communal divide according to nearly complete returns 
from local elections 
with all but 20 of the 566 council seats counted nationwide the 
gap between moderate and radical parties widened with moderates 
ahead 2to1 in both the protestant and roman catholic camps 
on the catholic side the larger social democratic labor party 
was showing the best election performance in its 20year history 
winning 120 seats compared to 101 in the last election in 1985 it 
had gained 3 percent to hold 208 percent of the total vote 
sinn fein the political backer of the militant irish republican 
army won 11 percent of the total vote down slightly from the 117 
percent it had in the last election the party was weaker in rural 
areas and was expected to lose 15 of its 59 council seats 
but in west belfast sinn feins traditional stronghold the 
party was 31 percent stronger and rose to an 187 percent share 
though the social democrats increased their belfast vote by 18 
percent sinn fein remained the capitals largest party and the 
council stayed protestant controlled 
the shift toward moderates appeared more pronounced on the 
protestant side where rev ian paisleys hardline democratic 
unionist party slumped by 63 percent and shed about 30 seats to 
105 
the larger more moderate official unionists gained 21 percent 
and was expected to finish with about 190 seats 
local elections matter little since the british government runs 
most of the provinces affairs but they are watched closely for 
pointers to the relative strengths of moderates and hardliners and 
any gain for sinn fein would sound alarm bells in london and dublin 
it does look as though there has been some move away from the 
extremes said tom king the cabinet minister who runs northern 
ireland 
but sinn feins alex maskey reelected in belfast said the 
vote in the capital endorsed his partys campaign to rid northern 
ireland of british rule but the 51seat belfast council remained 
firmly in protestant control 
among the more spectacular results were the social democratic 
and labor partys 78percent gain in londonderry another ira 
redoubt and sinn feins 47percent slide in enniskillen scene of 
a november 1987 ira bombing that killed 11 protestants and still 
arouses abhorrent memories 
in paisleys home town of ballymena his party lost 11 percent 
and three seats 
paisley said his voters were apathetic because they believe the 
british government is interested only in the balance of power 
concerning the ira 
the protestant parties are deeply embittered by a 1985 
angloirish agreement giving the irish government a say in northern 
irelands affairs they see ireland as a hostile 
catholicdominated state intent on dissolving their union with 
britain 
strong personalities proved able to override doctrinal divides 
in larne popular catholic priest pat buckley promised to serve 
all sectors of the community and won handsomely on a largely 
protestant vote 
in magherafelt social worker mary mcsorley romped home as an 
independent she had been kicked out of the social democratic and 
labor party for affronting irish nationalists by accepting a medal 
from queen elizabeth ii 
other moldbreakers were five selfstyled conservatives who 
pledged to attract mainland british parties into the province they 
argue this would strip ulster politics of their sectarian character 
and move them onto conventional leftright lines 
overall a pattern emerged of an electorate either indifferent 
turnout was down 4 percent or wanting moderate protestants and 
catholics to work together 
