<TEXT>
zhao ziyang in his first known rebellion against 
his mentor senior leader deng xiaoping has chosen to resign as 
head of the worlds largest communist party rather than endorse a 
crackdown on students demonstrating for democracy sources said 
as of friday night zhaos resignation offer had yet to be 
decided on by his colleagues in the party the chinese sources said 
however his failure to appear with premier li peng and other 
top party and government leaders when it was announced the military 
would move in to end the student unrest appeared to make zhaos 
break with the leadership irrevocable 
his rebellion contrasts with the fate of his predecessor hu 
yaobang who was forced to step down in january 1987 after failing 
to crack down on earlier nationwide student protests it was hus 
death april 15 that triggered the new student movement 
zhao 69 tried repeatedly in recent weeks to defuse mounting 
tensions between authorities suspicious of any unofficial political 
activity and students demanding a free press an end to official 
corruption and other reforms 
he reportedly sent representatives to campus to talk to students 
after their marches drew hundreds of thousands of cheering 
residents into the streets 
zhao was the first toplevel official to endorse student calls 
for dialogue after the party mouthpiece the peoples daily 
condemned the student movement as a planned conspiracy aimed at 
overthrowing the government 
he spoke april 27 as 150000 students and supporters marched 
triumphantly through beijing streets to tiananmen square in the 
first display of the widespread public support for their movement 
deng reportedly issued orders to stop that march but the crowds 
of citizens who swarmed to screen the students from police and 
soldiers made it impossible without bloodshed 
zhao used the student movement to trot out of the closet 
proposals for political reform that had been largely shelved since 
last summer worsening economic problems including inflation 
running at an annual rate of near 30 percent had weakened his hand 
and strengthened the position of officials such as premier li who 
favored moving more slowly on both economic and political reforms 
after students began their hunger strike in the square a week 
ago only zhao impressed the fasters as sincere in his pleas for 
them to stop and his promises that authorities were trying to 
implement reforms 
however the students said he spoke only as an individual and 
not for the government 
zhao was born in october 1919 to a landowning family in central 
chinas henan province he joined the communist party in 1938 and 
headed the party committee in his native county for most of the 
193745 chinajapan war 
unlike the previous generation of party leaders he did not take 
part in the 193435 long march the 7700mile trek from 
nationalist government troops in eastern china to the northwest 
after the communist victory in 1949 zhao spent most of his 
career in regional government and party posts he was purged during 
the 196676 far leftist cultural revolution as was deng but was 
rehabilitated in the 1970s 
he gained national prominence as party secretary and governor of 
dengs home province sichuan where he implemented dengs policies 
of dismantling communes and allowing private plots and bonuses for 
extra work 
deng brought zhao to beijing as vice premier in 1980 he became 
premier six months later replacing hua guofeng he was made acting 
party secretary in january 1987 after fellow reformer hu yaobang 
was forced to resign 
zhao was confirmed in the post at an october 1987 party 
conference in which his keynote speech emphasized increasing 
production over ideological issues he also announced dengs theory 
that china was in a primary stage of socialism during which 
time private ownership of businesses was permissible 
at the same congress a new party politburo standing committee 
was constituted made up of zhao premier li peng yao yilin qiao 
shi and hu qili 
by putting li and yao relative conservatives on the standing 
committee with liberalleaning zhao and hu qili deng may have been 
trying to prevent either faction from becoming powerful enough to 
discard him qiao a pragmatist was the swing vote 
the setup made deng an essential arbiter between the two 
factions a role he apparently relished 
in the end zhaos failure to win over the conservatives in the 
standing committee and dengs adamant refusal to compromise with 
the students may have forced zhao to step down 
</TEXT>
