<TEXT>
the message that seems to have 
emerged from northern irelands latest election is that peace is a 
long way off and people would like to get on with their lives in 
the meantime 
as the lengthy vote count wound up friday night a small but 
consistent shrinking was evident on the extremes of both sides of 
the religious divide and a strengthening of the center 
but there were also enough quirks and surprises to show that for 
many ordinary voters there are more immediate issues than ones 
national allegiances or the church one attends 
northern ireland averages nearly one election a year and rarely 
do they make a difference the protestants vote for protestant 
parties roman catholics for catholic parties 
the latest election to choose the 26 district councils 
contained no huge surprises 
the protestants who outnumber catholics 32 got most of the 
councils the main change was a slump of 6 percent for the rev ian 
paisleys hardline democratic unionists 
at the other end sinn fein the irish republican armys 
political backer lost some ground to the larger more moderate 
social democratic and labor party which turned in its best local 
election performance ever 
sinn feins losses were in the countryside in the catholic 
ghettoes of belfast its bastion the sinn fein vote held firm 
against sdlp advances and it remains the largest catholic party in 
a capital once again under protestant government 
the party leaders gathered in tv studios to discuss the outcome 
and engaged instead in a strident dialogue of the deaf 
paisley and james molyneux the two protestant party leaders 
stuck firmly to basics the 1985 angloirish agreement had to go 
before there could be any progress 
sdlp leader john hume retorted that the agreement was here to 
stay and he would brook no attempt to put it on ice 
there was no hint of compromise 
protestants revile the agreement because it gives the irish 
government a say in the running of northern ireland and most 
protestants regard ireland as a foreign country bent on dissolving 
northern irelands union with britain 
paisley argued that the british governments refusal to listen 
to protestant views on the agreement made voters apathetic and led 
to his partys slump 
but his critics said it was his disruptive antiagreement 
tactics and the paralysis they brought to local government that 
hurt him most 
people were most concerned about the daytoday issues cuts 
in housing attempts to interfere with the health service social 
security said hume he attributed the sdlps successes to the 
fact that those are the issues we fought the election on 
the election handed out many small victories that pointed to an 
electorate yearning for normalcy 
in larne for instance the rev pat buckley a popular catholic 
priest was elected on a largely protestant vote buckley promised 
to work for the community on the breadandbutter issues and his 
religion clearly made no difference 
in magherafelt mary mcsorley was elected as an independent 
after she was expelled from the sdlp for affronting irish 
nationalist sensibilities by accepting an honor from queen 
elizabeth ii 
the voters clearly admired her social work which won her the 
award and she was not only elected but holds the balance of power 
on the council 
in londonderry an ira stronghold protestant ken kerr defeated 
a machinepicked candidate with his promise to talk to catholic 
adversaries we have to start talking to people he said all 
around the world were seen as intransigent bigots and were not 
but we have to prove it 
sinn feins worst setback was in fermanagh the only district it 
captured outright in the 1985 local election it lost half its 
seats 
fermanagh happens to be where an ira bomb killed 11 protestants 
in november 1987 and sinn feins reputation was badly tarnished 
the protestant unionists now in charge of fermanagh have long 
advocated cooperation with the sdlp 
that is already happening in neighboring dungannon where 
unionist and sdlp councilors are in alliance to shut out the 
militants on both sides 
analyst paul arthur said fermanagh voters had looked at 
dungannon and taken that on board thats the sort of thing they 
want to see 
it gives you some hope for the future said a local sdlp 
leader austin currie 
there was a time when you only had to mention dungannon and 
you thought of divisiveness bigotry and discrimination he said 
id like to think that there may be a lesson for northern ireland 
as a whole that if people are given leadership they are prepared 
to follow the path of partnership and responsibilitysharing 
