<TEXT>
the youngest person to walk to the north pole said 
friday he wants to inspire kids in places like harlem where he 
grew up to believe in themselves and accomplish their dreams 
darryl roberts suffered frostbite blisters and pain for most of 
the 56day journey but he said he never thought of giving up 
because i believe so much in being able to go back and tell these 
kids the story hoping that it will inspire them 
five days after he set foot or more appropriately skis on 
the pole the 23yearold instructor in outdoor education was in 
balmy london with the seven other members of the arctic team to 
meet prime minister margaret thatcher 
the group walked 480 miles from cape aldrich the northernmost 
point in canada and encountered huge ice walls numerous cracks in 
the ice and temperatures as low as minus 67 
the message they delivered to mrs thatcher is one roberts said 
he wants to get across to american youngsters the pollution 
dangers facing the arctic are symptomatic of environmental dangers 
facing the world and young people must take responsibility for the 
planet they will inherit 
roberts said however i think i have to start with helping 
them to develop greater selfesteem greater selfconfidence 
because when you do that you want better things around you and you 
work toward that 
wearing sandals because of a blister on his heel and still 
sporting a few patches of the frostbite roberts said he has 
learned many things from the first international walk to the north 
pole 
one of the things i learned is that regardless of language 
barriers skin color differences cultural differences when human 
beings get together with a common goal in mind they can get 
that thing done regardless of how difficult the conditions he 
said 
thats exactly what we wanted to prove to the world that 
world powers like the soviet union and the united states can 
cooperate 
lets not count how many more missiles the other guys got 
lets get together on some of these world pollution problems and 
solve them because we can he said 
as a child in the new york city neighborhood of harlem roberts 
said i always knew that there was something more outside of 
where i was living 
helped by an ambitious mother he said he was able to attend a 
private high school he spent a year at northeastern university in 
boston studying engineering before dropping out to teach at outward 
bound an organization that offers wilderness experiences 
british explorer robert swan the expedition leader who became 
the first person to walk to the north and south poles said he 
selected the young man because i wanted darryl to represent a 
group of youngsters in america who no one really seems to be able 
to get through to and people that maybe have lost hope 
he said darryl proved that you can do anything if you really 
try and you keep going 
roberts said it was swans enormous moral support and the 
physical support of soviet physician mikhail malachov that helped 
him through an extremely difficult trip 
what was his feeling when he finally reached the pole 
i was so relieved that i wouldnt have to feel the pain 
anymore and i was almost wrapped in tears because my feet were 
killing me he said 
second was the elation that the entire team had gotten there 
together and that was true to one of our objectives of 
international cooperation 
when roberts returns to new york next week he hopes to start 
lecturing and he would like to meet president bush but his future 
still is uncertain 
this was an incredible risk he said i think im going to 
do something a little more relaxed from now on 
</TEXT>
