<TEXT>
senators made extra money last year selling 
hay pitching jokes collecting pensions writing books and making 
speeches lots of speeches but none had to rely solely on a 
senate salary 
according to financial disclosure statements made public friday 
perhaps onethird of the 100 senators are millionaires and most 
others are wealthy 
most have impressive investments 
and most routinely accepted speaking fees and travel 
reimbursements from specialinterest groups 
heres how some senators supplemented their 89500 senate 
paychecks last year 
alfonse damato rny earned 15000 as a lecturer at cw 
post college in long island ny 
donald riegle dmich made 21 speeches at 1000 apiece to 
washington campus a nonprofit educational organization that 
conducts seminars 
paul simon dill reported 3042 in residuals from four 
appearances on saturday night live 
charles grassley riowa grossed 65000 from five farms but 
after subtracting expenses was left with only 6000 
dale bumpers dark reaped 1760 selling hay off his farm 
bennett johnston dla who heads the senate energy committee 
pocketed 377 in oilwell royalties 
senate majority leader george j mitchell dmaine earned 
22500 in royalties from men of zeal a book he wrote with his 
maine colleague republican sen william cohen which reflected 
their service on the senate committee that investigated the 
irancontra affair 
cohen listed 25763 in royalties including some still coming 
in from a novel he coauthored with exsen gary hart 
alan cranston dcalif received 62906 in pension from his 
service as a california state official and 18246 in social 
security benefits 
robert kerrey dneb who lost a leg in the vietnam war 
reported 18972 from a navy pension 
almost all the 95 senators who filed the required statements 
five were granted extensions reported receiving honoraria which 
usually were fees for making speeches to schools churches and 
specialinterest groups 
sam nunn dga chairman of the senate armed services 
committee listed 46950 in such fees including 10000 from 
elements of the defense industry under the rules he could keep 
only 35800 so he gave 11686 to charity 
richard lugar of indiana senior republican on the agriculture 
