<TEXT>
iran is suing the united states in 
the world court for financial compensation for the 290 people 
killed when the uss vincennes shot down an iranian airliner a 
court official said friday 
tehrans move came less than a year after the iran air jet was 
hit by two american missiles and exploded thousands of feet above 
the persian gulf all passengers and crew perished in the july 3 
1988 incident 
irans fundamentalist government has asked the court to rule 
that the government of the united states is responsible to pay 
compensation to the islamic republic to the amount to be 
determined by the court as measured by the injuries suffered by 
the islamic republic and the bereaved families 
a copy of irans request which was filed wednesday was 
obtained by the associated press 
iran did not provide an estimate of the damage suffered 
according to e safavi a spokesman for the iranian embassy in the 
hague 
at the time of the incident president reagan offered 
compensation to relatives of the victims but he ruled out any role 
for the iranian government in settling damage claims 
it was not immediately known whether the bush administration was 
planning to take part in the proceedings 
thomas hodges a spokesman for the us embassy here said a 
copy of the iranian application was sent to the secretary of state 
in washington where it is being studied he declined further 
comment 
on friday the world court was considering when to proceed with 
the case hearings do not begin until arguments have been filed in 
writing a process that usually takes months 
the world court is the judicial branch of the united nations 
officially known as the international court of justice it has no 
enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its 
rulings 
the crew of the vincennes erroneously identified an iranian 
passenger airbus plane as an iranian air force f14 fighter plane 
and shot it down 
irans application to the world court charges the united states 
has violated an international treaty on terrorism against airplanes 
the 1971 geneva convention for the suppression of unlawful acts 
against the safety of civil aviation 
it is the second case in a decade pitting the united states 
against iran at the world court 
ten years ago the carter administration filed suit against iran 
over the fate of 55 american diplomats held hostage at the us 
embassy in tehran the affair which made washington break 
relations with tehran 
iran which did not appear in court was ordered to immediately 
release the hostages tehran ignored the ruling the hostages 
ultimately were freed in january 1980 after an elaborate deal was 
negotiated with the help of algeria 
the united states withdrew from proceedings in the other major 
world court case in which it was involved in 1984 when nicaragua 
sought a halt to us support for the rebels known as contras 
only days before the complaint was filed the reagan 
administration canceled its acceptance of world court jurisdiction 
in central american affairs the court sided with the sandinista 
government two years later 
only 49 of the 159 un member nations have accepted the courts 
authority as compulsory in settling conflicts between states the 
united states is one of them 
