<TEXT>
policymakers at the federal reserve in march 
voted to hold interest rates steady unless the slowing of economic 
growth proved inadequate to restrain inflation according to 
minutes of the meeting released friday 
the federal open market committee noting early signs of a 
slackening in economic growth voted 111 at its march 28 meeting 
to leave rates unchanged initially 
but most members felt monetary policy should be adjusted more 
readily and promptly toward greater restraint than toward ease 
the minutes said 
the committee which meets in secret eight times a year sets 
monetary policy for the federal reserve whose main job is to fight 
inflation 
in march 1988 the fed began to gradually push interest rates 
upward in an attempt to cool the economy and thus curb inflation 
since then shortterm rates have risen three percentage points and 
economic growth has shown signs of softening 
most analysts believe the fed is holding off on further 
tightening of credit while it analyzes how the economic slowdown 
will affect inflation 
price increases have been sharp so far this year the consumer 
price index rose at an annual rate of 66 percent over the first 
four months of 1989 up from the 44 percent price increases 
registered in 1987 and 1988 
fomc members in march found recent price increases to be 
disappointing if not entirely unexpected but many wanted to 
wait for evidence to accumulate on the possible need for a further 
tightening of policy the minutes said 
some members felt the current slowing of the expansion might 
be inadequate to restrain inflationary pressures the minutes 
said 
since the march meeting signs of a slowdown have become more 
pronounced and analysts believe the fed is unlikely to push rates 
higher 
the fomc met again this week but minutes of that meeting will 
not be released until after the committees next meeting in early 
july the committee is made up of the seven federal reserve 
governors and the presidents of five of its 12 regional banks 
the committee issues directives that govern the open market 
operations of the federal reserve bank of new york through the 
purchase of government securities from banks the central bank 
influences the amount of reserves the banks have to make loans from 
and thus the price of those loans interest rates 
the committees march directive to the new york bank said the 
fomc seeks to maintain the existing degree of pressure on reserve 
positions 
however it added that somewhat greater reserve restraint 
would or slightly lesser reserve restraint might be acceptable 
in fed parlance the word would carries stronger implications 
than does might 
the lone dissenter from the march vote was fed gov martha 
seger who opposed the tilt toward further increases in interest 
rates according to the minutes 
ms seger earlier this month told a group of home builders that 
with the recent softening in economic growth we need to be very 
wary of slipping over the edge into recession 
a growing number of private economists have expressed concern 
that the feds antiinflation campaign could have the unintended 
effect of causing a recession the latest survey of 50 leading 
economists by the blue chip economic indicators newsletter found 
that twothirds expect a recession to begin this year or in 1990 
</TEXT>
