a senior west german official said 
friday that washington and bonn have worked out a formula for a 
facesaving compromise in the dispute over natos shortrange 
nuclear missiles 
under the compromise discussed during the washington visit of 
west german defense minister gerhard stoltenberg the us 
administration would accept the idea of negotiations with the 
kremlin if west germany makes clear it does not seek a third 
zero immediate elimination of shortrange weapons 
the reported agreement is mostly symbolic as no date has been 
proposed for the start of superpower talks on the missiles and the 
talks remain conditional on an unspecified improvement in the 
eastwest balance of conventional arms the source said 
but west germany and the united states have been arguing over 
the issue of shortrange missiles for months and the washington 
talks appear to have found a common position for the two allies to 
take with them to the nato summit in brussels on may 2930 
it is no longer disputed that there should be negotiations on 
shortrange weapons said the bonn official familiar with 
stoltenbergs talks in washington but they the talks should be 
prepared carefully and in relation to conventional reductions 
the officials explanation of the agreement suggested that us 
and west german officials had backed down from their previous 
positions 
stoltenberg flew to washington wednesday to meet with us 
secretary of state james a baker iii and defense secretary dick 
cheney 
the west german defense minister appointed only a month ago 
was reported to have taken with him a new plan for resolving the 
dispute that has separated bonn and washington and caused a rift 
within the nato alliance 
stoltenberg was to propose a link between a reduction of soviet 
troops and tanks in europe and the start of shortrange 
negotiations the bonn official said that proposal was accepted in 
principle by the us officials stoltenberg met with 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev has begun withdrawing 
50000 troops and 5000 tanks from eastern europe and has announced 
that the kremlin will unilaterally cut its shortrange nuclear 
arsenal by 500 warheads 
however us officials have said both gestures fall short of 
what is needed to warrant revision of nato defense policy 
baker told reporters in washington earlier this week that he 
considered shortrange negotiations a mistake under the current 
circumstances 
washington contends nato should stand by its flexible 
response doctrine or retention of some nuclear weapons in europe 
for use in repelling a potential attack by the east blocs superior 
conventional forces 
but as both military blocs have begun dismantling their 
intermediaterange nuclear missiles under the 1987 inf treaty the 
burden of hosting a nuclear option has shifted to west germany 
where most of natos shortrange systems are deployed 
of the 88 shortrange lance missile launchers stationed in 
central europe by nato 76 are in west germany 
bonn has refused to go along with a nato plan to upgrade the 
lance missiles which have a range of about 75 miles with new 
rockets capable of reaching targets as far away as 300 miles until 
the superpowers take some interim steps to reduce the weapons they 
have deployed in europe 
natos plan is widely opposed in west germany for fear it will 
damage improving relations with eastern europe and chances for 
further progress on arms control progress 
soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze threatened during a 
visit to bonn last weekend that the kremlin might halt destruction 
of its ss23s one of the missiles being removed under the inf 
agreement if nato goes ahead with the modernization project 
it was not immediately clear whether the compromise reportedly 
worked out by stoltenberg and us officials on thursday would be 
acceptable to other members of the 16nation nato alliance or even 
if the junior political parties in chancellor helmut kohls 
coalition would go along 
