<TEXT>
the agriculture department said friday it has 
approved a permit for the university of kentucky to conduct a field 
test of tobacco containing a mouse liver gene that regulates the 
concentration of heavy metals 
eventually officials said the research could lead to a 
reduction in disease by making it possible to keep soilborne toxic 
metals largely in the uneaten roots of leafy vegetables 
heavy metals have been implicated in many disease processes 
and can be consumed by humans when eating leafy vegetables like 
spinach or lettuce said larry b slagle acting administrator of 
the departments animal and plant health inspection service 
tobacco can be used as a model crop to help understand 
genetically engineered traits before transferring them to other 
plant species he said 
the mouse liver gene instructs the plant to make a protein 
called metallothionein which binds tightly to heavy metals such as 
cadmium mercury and copper in greenhouse tests university of 
kentucky scientists found that the protein lowered the level of 
cadmium on tobacco leaves by about a fourth 
slagle said the field trials will be in lexington ky 
beginning in late may and continuing through the summer 
</TEXT>
