<TEXT>
the brownrobed nun moves from shrub to 
shrub carefully watering a welltended row of plants along the 
edge of a broad lawn in the middle stands a 23foot wooden cross 
but the serenity of the scene vanishes just a few feet behind 
her 
there stand the gray barbedwiretopped fence and square guard 
towers of auschwitz headquarters of a nazi concentration camp 
complex where 4 million people died from 1940 to 1945 
and the peaceful hollowedout lawn with the flowers and the 
cross where the nun works is in fact a former gravel pit where 
political prisoners were gunned down by their nazi executioners in 
194041 
the 14 nuns of the barefoot carmelite monastery built in a 
former nazi storehouse on the auschwitz camp perimeter are not 
answering questions these days reporters are politely turned away 
at the gate 
they are at the center of an international controversy 
their very presence at the camp is deeply offensive to jews who 
resent christian religious symbols at the place that was the main 
engine of hitlers final solution the site of death for an 
estimated 25 million people whose only crime was being jewish 
calls for the nuns removal were repeated by jewish leaders in 
western europe israel and the united states this spring after the 
roman catholic church missed a february deadline for moving the 
sisters to an interfaith prayer and education center to be built at 
an undetermined site farther from the camp 
the agreement to move the nuns and build the prayer center 
within two years was signed in geneva on feb 22 1987 at a 
meeting of 18 jewish and roman catholic leaders and the removal of 
the convent was to be carried out by the archbishop of krakow 
cardinal franciszek macharski 
but now a polish newspaper is waging a campaign to keep the nuns 
at the cloister they founded in 1984 and the issue is gaining 
support from some residents who argue that the nuns are not harming 
anyone 
the newspaper slowo powszechne universal word the organ of 
the progovernment lay catholic group pax published an open letter 
assailing the plans to move the nuns 
the letter accusing the jewish side of illegal demands 
to ruthlessly carry out an illegal eviction says that the 
nuns should stay because the building they occupy is not actually 
within the camp also it argues the main killing site for jews 
was not in auschwitz itself but at the muchlarger subsidiary camp 
birkenenau about a mile away 
but krzysztof sliwinski a catholic journalist for the liberal 
church weekly tygodnik powszechny maintained such arguments are 
disingenuous 
although it isnt on the strict grounds it is just two or 
three meters beyond the fence he said symbolically it is in 
the camp 
sliwinski said he does not expect the slowo powszechne campaign 
to alter the plans to move the convent which were confirmed by the 
church episcopate earlier this year but he sees the controversy as 
symptomatic of the wider problems in catholicjewish relations in 
poland 
here there is a sort of unresolved tension between catholics 
and jews he said the relationship is characterized by deep 
misunderstandings resentments and mutual ignorance 
poland is overwhelmingly catholic and poles have difficulty 
imagining why anyone would object to the nuns being next to the 
camp where so many people were killed including roman catholic 
priests and nuns and tens of thousands of nonjewish poles 
sliwinski said that one aspect of the problem is that after the 
decision was made to move the monastery it was never properly 
explained to the people 
jews number barely 10000 people in poland and are virtually 
invisible in social life the nazis killed 3 million of the 
countrys 34 million jews and most of the survivors emigrated 
the last wave after a communist antisemitic purge in 1968 
at the convent itself a theater before world war ii there are 
no outward signs that the nuns are planning to move they have 
planted their garden for another year and workmen moving in and out 
apparently are making improvements inside a way of the cross 
with 13 stations has been put next to the camps walls 
the church hierarchy still says it intends to move the nuns but 
said in a bishops statement it had run into to difficulties 
the difficulties are not a manifestation of ill will 
the statement said in part they result from administrative 
formalities in part from the history of oswiecim itself from its 
significance and the symbolic meaning of this place for the polish 
nation 
as oswiecim is for jews a symbol of shoah remembrance for 
poles it remains the place of bloody martyrdom of the polish nation 
for us poles both the construction of the center as well as 
the presence of the carmelite nuns there in the spirit of the 
agreement signed feb 22 1987 in geneva have a great significance 
for the future 
