<DOCNO> AP890519-0209 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the submarine uss squalus lay on the 
atlantic floor and in the forward torpedo room gerald mclees and 
his shipmates sat quietly conserving oxygen and hoping that 
someone would realize their routine test dive had gone tragically 
wrong 
shortly before as the crew of 59 had prepared to test the 
boats ability to submerge within 60 seconds while running at high 
speed everything was normal said mclees recalling the 
sinking 50 years ago tuesday he was then a 25yearold chief 
electricians mate 
as the subs trial run began 13 miles off the new hampshire 
coast a panel of green lights indicated that all the hull openings 
were closed and the captain lt oliver naquin gave the order to 
dive 
suddenly water began pouring into the engine rooms 
apparently 31inchwide valves used to draw air in when the sub 
was on the surface had opened without tripping warning indicators 
in the control room an inquiry later identified the cause as a 
mechanical malfunction 
my reaction was to get everything shut off said allen carl 
bryson who at the time was a 21yearold machinists mate second 
class if there was any panic it was all in the end we didnt 
have time for things like that 
mclees and bryson and their shipmates worked to seal off their 
forward battery compartment but water was not the only menace they 
faced as the sub tilted bow up and descended 
chief electricians mate lawrence gainer noticed that seawater 
had shorted out one of the ships two batteries creating a rapid 
voltage drain 
he wedged himself into a narrow crawl space to shut off the 
power 
it was two big switches he had to pull when he pulled one of 
them it threw such an arc that the arc didnt break until he 
pulled the other one mclees said 
the light seared his eyes damaging them permanently but 
gainer probably saved the boat bryson said 
even so the trouble was just beginning for the squalus before 
its ordeal was over 26 of the 59 crewmen would be lost the rest 
credited their survival to the first nontest use of a special 
rescue chamber 
naquins submarine now without light or communications he 
ordered bryson to herd crewmen forward as chlorine gas formed from 
a seawater reaction in the battery compartment 
petty officer 3rd class lloyd maness was on watch near a 
critical hatch between the control room and the subs rapidly 
flooding rear compartments according to a 1988 article in the 
journal naval history as maness strained to close the 200pound 
hatch he heard panicked voices calling keep it open keep it 
open writer carl la vo recounted 
five men staggered uphill halfswimming to safety maness 
then pulled the steel door shut behind it no one would survive 
la vo wrote 
the lack of power kept the crew from signaling the portsmouth 
naval shipyard in kittery maine but authorities realized there 
was trouble when the squalus failed to send a surfacing message one 
hour after it announced it was starting its dive 
the squalus sent a buoy to the surface with a telephone line 
attached and periodically fired red smoke rockets 
the sculpin the squalus sister ship was dispatched from 
portsmouth and lookouts spotted the smoke rockets 
some 240 feet below the squalus crew was cheered by the sudden 
churning of the sculpins engines we knew somebody had spotted 
us anyway mclees said 
but it was 23 hours after the sinking before the submarine 
tender falcon arrived from new london conn carrying the mccann 
rescue chamber a nineton diving bell that would be lowered to a 
hatch on the sub and used to bring up survivors 
mclees was one of the first to ride up bryson and naquin were 
in the last group 
with navy divers john mihalowski and william badders inside the 
bell made a final descent for the hazardous mission of opening a 
hatch to check for survivors in rear compartments the two found 
water right up to the neck of the hatch concluding that 
there couldnt possibly be any life down there badders now 
dead told a naval institute interviewer in 1971 
mihalowski and badders received the medal of honor for their 
role in the rescue 
relief changed to sorrow as the survivors returned to the 
shipyard 
mclees single at the time watched other men joyfully reunited 
with their wives on the pier 
of course there were some there their husbands didnt come 
back he said 
mclees returned to the squalus less than a year later after the 
boat was salvaged and rechristened the sailfish he served aboard 
during seven world war ii patrols in the pacific 
the sailfish was decommissioned at portsmouth on oct 27 1945 
its conning tower was placed in a park at the shipyard which holds 
an annual memorial service 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

