fears that hong kong 
investors and immigrants will change the placid ways of this scenic 
pacific city have surged into the open with charges of racism not 
far behind 
mayor gordon campbell who is sponsoring a series of public 
forums intended to calm the escalating controversy said people are 
looking for an easy way to explain the rapid changes tied to the 
citys growth 
i think theres no question that people are concerned he 
said in an interview i think the fears are real so lets 
shine the light on them 
soaring housing prices and high profile projects in commercial 
real estate in the past year have made asian specifically hong 
kong investment the hottest topic in the area 
the local newspapers are devoting full pages to letters to the 
editor about the issue 
native vancouverites will be made to feel like strangers in 
their own city as the influx of asians and their capital freezes 
them out wrote one reader to the province 
this is a golden opportunity to absorb investment and skilled 
professionals said another on the same page it is of 
paramount importance that british columbia not just become a 
prosperous province but also maintain a harmonious multicultural 
environment for all its inhabitants old and new 
the debate covers a wide range including the increasing number 
of asian children in neighborhood schools 
perhaps no project has attracted as much attention as the 16 
billion pacific place project on the false creek downtown 
waterfront lands where expo 86 attracted attention to the city 
li kashing the hong kong magnate who is the projects major 
financier purchased the lands from the city for the canadian 
dollar equivalent of 269 million the government must bear the 
substantial cost of removing industrial waste from the site 
theres an old chinese saying that a big tree gathers the 
wind stanley kwok a senior vice president of concord pacific 
developments ltd said in explaining the attention paid his 
companys massive project 
wherever theres change one thing will stand out said 
kwok who has been in vancouver for 21 years just like any north 
american neighborhood nobody wants change 
about 20 percent of the vancouver area population of 12 million 
is of chinese origin many of them people whose families have been 
in canada for generations 
the external affairs department in ottawa has estimated that 
investment from hong kong will increase sharply to 33 billion in 
canada this year from 2 billion in 1988 
always in the equation is 1997 when control of hong kong goes 
back to china from britain 
