boeing salesmen also are working on getting the united order for 
later this year well be showing them what we have in the 
salesroom ms reese said 
wolf said united would receive its first five 767300ers in 
1991 two more in 1992 eight in 1993 and one in 1994 four of the 
jets on option are to be delivered in 1994 five in 1995 and seven 
in 1996 
the planes will be powered by pratt amp whitney engines 
boeing and its two major competitors mcdonnell douglas corp 
and europes airbus industrie have been blessed with a crush of 
orders in recent years due to concerns about older aircraft 
forecasts of continued rapid growth of air travel and a need for 
planes to meet tougher noise standards and to be more economical 
boeing and mcdonnell douglas both have suffered delays in 
delivering new aircraft boeing with its 747400 jumbo jet and 
mcdonnell douglas with its md11 widebody but boeing officials say 
they dont expect delays to spread to other assembly lines 
ms reese said uniteds new order was anticipated and isnt 
going to impact the production line because we plan things like 
this in advance 
phil condit boeing commercial airplanes executive vice 
president said in a briefing last week that boeing has 
substantially met its revised schedule for delivering the new 747s 
though it has had to negotiate penalties with at least four 
customers 
condit said those delays were due in great part to overly 
ambitious plans to introduce four different variations of the jumbo 
jet simultaneously 
boeing says it is increasing production rates from 27 jets a 
month to 34 by mid1990s and is spending 11 billion on capital 
improvements this year including major upgrades at its renton 737 
and 757 plant and at its widebody factory in everett wash 
condit said boeings production schedules are being planned 
years in advance and that the company is carefully increasing 
production so as not overwhelm its own and its suppliers capacity 
